HE man whom thou, dear Muse of song, Didst at his birth regard with smiling calm, Shall win no glory in the Isthmian throng, From lusty wrestlers bearing off the palm, Nor ever, reining steads of fire, shall he In swift Achaian car roll on victoriously.

Nor him shall warfare's stern renown,

Nor baffled menaces of mighty kings, Bear to the Capitol with laurel crown ;

But streams that kiss with gentle murmurings Rich Tibur's vale‚—thick wood, and mossy brake, Him of the AEolian lyre shall worthy master make.
